As an inevitable by-product of the real thing, the supply of Atari fake 
demos remains a dripping tap of fun or fecklessness, depending on your 
point of view.. Some of the following may well make you want to laugh 
out loud, some of them make you want to leave your lunch on the 
pavement instead!

 
 Ipir 'Rump Mapper' demo..

Okay, what can we say, really scraping the barrel of enthusiasm here, 
with a demo that linked the recently popular 'bump-mapping' effect with 
the witless pun 'rump'.. Oh dear....

Kicking it into life, and a certain charm pastes itself across the 
screen, the pleasingly childish visuals are perfectly complemented by 
the nursery rhyme music.. That is, if you are prepared to accept a 
nursery rhyme written and performed by a recently defrocked Swedish 
priest going around under the stage name of "Dr Demented"!

(What he was defrocked for need not concern you, dear reader..)

The demo builds up to its 'climax', a drunken trouser-dropper caught in 
the act and lit up by a pseudo lighting effect, the 'rump-map' in 
question!

A kind of torus soon follows, and various greetings, which are best 
hastily passed over to finish..

This faketro manages to blend in its various audio and visual elements 
as cleverly as its more serious brothers.. Very funny from the first, 
and a rare joke demo that manages to rise above the 'one joke funny for 
one time only' label that clings shroudlike to so many of its 
brethren.. 

 70% - It kicks rump!


 Da Boosters 'Spacebot'..

Yet another production that might well describe itself as 'not rocket 
science'.. The name 'Spacebot' induces a profound fear of yet more 
anally inspired faketro antics, but you are not to worry..

What you do get, is a hilarious parody of the Beachie Boys summer hit 
'Intergalac-sick'.. A reasonably faithful recreation of the video and 
song, subject to the processing limits, graphical and sound power of 
the Faclon '30.. This includes extra hardware never seen in the 
standard Falcon, such as 'tone-flatteners' to stop the music 
overwhelming the majority of cheap hi-fi equipment.. These particular 
variants of the basic Falcon are very rare, with the single export 
batch ending up in an ice-floe somewhere in Greenland! 

There are cunningly scrolling fore and aft bits as well as the main 
attraction.. Unfortunately, the Beachie Boys tribute band involved in 
the making of this faketro, were all squashed flat by a cartoon robot..

 65% - Not the top of the class, but not the 'spacebot' either!


 (The) Nun Demo..

I have a whole bag of puns ready for this demo, how about 'Nun but the 
brave' would attempt this kind of subject matter, or a 'Nunplussed' 
demo censor tries to get to grips with shocktro!

Moving on to 'Nun to five', as fake demo makers reveal it was all 
created in office hours..

Not forgetting their possible planned release for the year before the 
millenium in 'Nun-teen Nun-ety Nine'!

Fake demo? - Very well then, fake review!

Alright, it's rude, very rude, and blurry, the sort of effect that you 
might see if you persist in certain forms of self-abuse for too long, 
or so those stiff-looking Victorian era self-help manuals once said!

 60% - It's over far too quickly! (MSG, what're you doing in this          
         review?)


 A Small Brainless Gag..

A quick (written less in 1 hour) anti-PC 'tribute' demo, modelled on 
the famous 'Things not to do' cartoon demo, but only one scene of the 
hapless owner putting his Wintel box of joy in the dustbin.. All over 
so quickly..

Anyone fancy doing a full 'Things not to do' style jokefest, with loads 
of different horrible but hilarious things happening to those expensive 
Window boxes.. How about it?

 50% - So short, but so sweet!
